      "is_answer_order_important": false,
      "stimulus_html": "",
      "stem_html": "<p>In step 2 of the citric acid cycle (Figure 29.14), <i>cis</i>-aconitate reacts with water to give (2<i>R</i>,3<i>S</i>)-isocitrate. Does  –OH add from the Re face of the double bond or from the Si face? What about  –H? Does the addition of water occur with syn or anti geometry?</p>\n<img src=\"https://exercises.openstax.org/rails/active_storage/blobs/proxy/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBdXNaIiwiZXhwIjpudWxsLCJwdXIiOiJibG9iX2lkIn19--ed9c56a128e70e8def6eccf4b4edd13ffe91c92d/OChem_29_EC_016.jpg\" alt=\"Cis-aconitate having a three-carbon chain and a double bond reacts with water to form (2 R,3 S)-Isocitrate. The double bond is replaced by single bond in the product.\">",
